english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Master Mok-eun of the Eastern Kingdom
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There exists the natural principle of heaven and earth, and thus there exists the natural form of heaven and earth. The sun, moon, and stars possess it to illuminate all things; wind, rain, frost, and dew possess it to transform; mountains and waters possess it to flow and stand; grasses and trees possess it to flourish and blossom; fish and birds possess it to fly and leap. All the myriad things that bear sound and fill the realm between heaven and earth each possess their own natural form. In man, this manifests greatly in the beauty of ritual, music, punishment, and governance, and subtly in the dignity of bearing and the elegance of words. Nothing fails to express this principle. Things attain but a single aspect, while man attains the whole. Yet constrained by the limits of temperament and the bounds of learning, few can preserve this wholeness without becoming partial. The sage is like heaven and earth itself. The Six Classics contain principles so complete and forms so refined that nothing surpasses them. Before the Qin and Han, the vital force flowed as one; after the Wei and Cao, that great force dispersed, the grand order collapsed, and both form and principle became obscured. When the Tang arose, learning flourished anew, and writers succeeded one another. At first each pursued only their singular manner, scarcely establishing a name. But when Li Bai, Du Fu, Han Yu, and Liu Zongyuan came forth, they mingled their work like vast waters, encompassing ten thousand forms and kinds in unified brilliance. The Song's Ouyang Xiu and Su Shi also rose to rival and surpass the ancients. Alas, how glorious this age!

    In our Eastern realm, Master Mok-eun possessed pure essence and clear spirit, vast learning and penetrating understanding. What he held within harmonized with utmost refinement; what he cultivated matched supreme greatness. Thus when these flowed forth into his writings, they overflow with ease and abundance, profound yet boundless. His brilliance outshines sun and moon; his transformations surpass wind and rain; his solidity towers like mountains; his vastness flows like rivers. His beauty blooms like flowers on grass and trees; his vitality moves like the dance of birds and fish; his richness encompasses all things, each receiving their natural perfection. In matters of ritual, music, punishment, and governance; in the principles of humanity, righteousness, and virtue—all are refined and gathered at their ultimate height. Could any but one who inherited the pure essence of heaven and earth, who penetrated the profound depths of the sages, who guided his carriage along the paths of Ouyang and Su, and ascended to the chamber of Han and Liu achieve such mastery? Since learning came to our Eastern realm, none has surpassed Master Mok-eun. Truly, he stands supreme!
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''Six Classics'' (육적) refers to the canonical texts of Confucian learning: the Book of Changes, Book of History, Book of Poetry, Book of Rites, Spring and Autumn Annals, and the ritual texts.'
    - Li Bai, Du Fu, Han Yu, and Liu Zongyuan represent the apex of Tang dynasty literary achievement, marking the moment when Chinese poetry and prose attained both technical mastery and spiritual depth.
    - Ouyang Xiu and Su Shi were celebrated Song dynasty scholars and writers known for their refinement and moral eloquence.
    - Mok-eun (牧隱) refers to Yi Saek (이색), a major Korean literatus of the Goryeo-Joseon transition period.
